<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="93" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="93">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="93">Spain.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="93">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">Note</emphasis>
: Isolates of 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. rhizoidum" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" rank="species" species="rhizoidum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">L. rhizoidum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from pine-infesting bark beetles in Spain were initially identified as 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. olivaceum" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" rank="species" species="olivaceum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">L. olivaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on ITS sequences by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1139/W07-001" author="Romon, P" journalOrPublisher="Canadian Journal of Microbiology" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" pagination="756 - 767" refId="B44" refString="Romon, P, Zhou, XD, Iturrondobeitia, JC, Wingfield, MJ, Goldarazena, A, 2007. Ophiostoma species (Ascomycetes: Ophiostomatales) associated with bark beetles (Coleoptera: Scolytinae) colonizing Pinusradiata in northern Spain. Canadian Journal of Microbiology 53: 756 - 767" title="Ophiostoma species (Ascomycetes: Ophiostomatales) associated with bark beetles (Coleoptera: Scolytinae) colonizing Pinusradiata in northern Spain." url="https://doi.org/10.1139/W07-001" volume="53" year="2007">Romon et al. (2007)</bibRefCitation>
. Our data showed them to be distinct from that species. This species produced more abundant and longer rhizoids than others in the complex.
</paragraph>
